33 (b) Petitions for district wide and statewide recounts of the September 1, 2026 state
34 primary shall be submitted to the appropriate local election officials for certification not later
35 than 3:00 P.M. on Thursday, September 3, 2026 and local election officials shall complete
36 certification not later than 12:00 P.M. on Friday, September 4, 2026. Thereafter, certified
37 petitions shall be filed with the state secretary not later than 5:00 P.M. on Friday, September 4,
38 2026. If the state secretary determines that the contest is eligible for a statewide or district wide
39 recount, the state secretary shall notify the local election officials who shall complete the recount
40 and shall notify the state secretary of the results of the recount not later than 5:00 P.M. on Friday,
41 September 11, 2026.
42 (c) Notwithstanding section 135 of chapter 54 of the General Laws, a board of registrars
43 shall only provide 2 days’ notice of the date, time and location of the recount to each candidate
44 for the office for which the recount has been petitioned. Electronic notice shall be sufficient.
45 SECTION 7. Notwithstanding sections 8 to 10, inclusive, of chapter 55B of the General
46 Laws or any other general or special law to the contrary, the state ballot law commission shall
47 notify candidates of any objections filed to nominations at the September 1, 2026 state primary
48 not later than 5:00 P.M. on Friday, September 4, 2026. Notice of the commission hearings shall
49 be given by telephone and electronic mail. Hearings on objections shall be held on Wednesday,
50 September 9, 2026 and decisions shall be rendered not later than 5:00 P.M. on Friday, September
51 11, 2026.
52 SECTION 8. Notwithstanding any general or special law to the contrary, local election
53 officials shall transmit absentee ballots to voters covered under the federal Uniformed and
54 Overseas Citizens Absentee Voting Act, 42 U.S.C. §§ 1973ff-1 et seq., whose applications were
